Right-wing populists' triumph in Austria, combined with 29 per cent
The significant weakening of both parties of the existing grand coalition and the significant strengthening of right-wing populist parties brought Sunday's early parliamentary elections in Austria, according to the first preliminary results.
The Austrian People's Party (ÖVP) suffered particularly strong losses, where the position of current President Wilhelm Molterer is seriously shaken.
On the contrary, the electoral leader of the Union for the Future of Austria (BZÖ), the Carinthian Governor Jörg Haider is preparing a triumphant return to national politics.
According to preliminary results, the strongest party in the country of the Social Democratic Party (SPÖ) remains with 29.8 percent of the vote, but loses 5.5 percent of the vote against the last elections in 2006.
The ÖVP lost even worse, losing almost nine percent of the vote with 25.6 percent.
These are the worst results of both of these big parties in Austrian post-war history and, especially among the People's Party, who have triggered early elections, a literally disastrous outcome.
Even at the beginning of July, when the ÖVP came out of the coalition, the People's Party had a considerable lead in the preferences over the SPÖ.
Voters, however, apparently punished them for letting the government fail.
Already in the first reactions to the results, there was speculation about the possible resignation of the party chairman and the current vice-chancellor Wilhelm Molterer.
Observers believe this could happen as early as Monday at an emergency meeting of the party bureau.
Such a development would probably facilitate the path to the increasingly likely starting point from the election result, i.e. to the renewal of the grand coalition of the SPÖ and ÖVP.
However, due to the strengthening of the two right-wing populist parties - the Free (FPÖ) won tentatively 18 percent and BZÖ eleven percent of the vote - at the same time, the Social Democrats expressed concern about the repetition of 1999, when the People's Party agreed with the populists (at that time it was still united, in 2005 it split off from the BZÖ) on a joint government that even provoked sanctions from the European Union.
Haider is clearly betting on this development, who has already said he is ready to cooperate with any party and assumes a return to Vienna to national politics.
The Green Party also came to parliament, but it lost slightly and fell among the Austrian political parties from third to fifth place.
None of the other parties, apparently, surpassed the four percent threshold and did not make it to parliament.
