The first virtual operator will arrive in the Czech Republic this year.
Maybe
The mobile market in the Czech Republic is quite advanced and our operators offer virtually all services as their partners in Western Europe.
Still, we're missing something here - a virtual operator that would make the classic ones cheaper.
Maybe he won't miss him for long.
We have written many times about the fact that Czech operators are among the most expensive in Europe.
After all, this was confirmed by CTU, which pointed out that the price of SMS in our country is higher than in the rest of the Union.
After the latest steps by the European Commission in the field of regulation of roaming charges, there may be a paradoxical situation - for some customers of Czech mobile operators, SMS from abroad will be cheaper than at home.
How is it possible that prices in the Czech Republic are so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, there is no competition that really wants to go into battle.
It may sound paradoxical, we have three mobile networks and penetrations high above 100%.
Mobile operators, on the other hand, like to pretend that the Czech market is extremely competitive.
Pavel Dvořák, Chairman of the Council of the Czech Telecommunication Office (ČTÚ), often acknowledges them, and has said several times in the past that there is no place for another operator in the Czech Republic.
It is probably true that a classic operator with its own network probably does not have much chance (after all, it would probably be difficult to find frequencies).
But there is another option - a virtual operator.
It is the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market that brought a significant reduction in prices, which were then also affected by classical operators.
Even before the entry of pikes such as Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile, similar voices were heard in the UK as in the UK.
However, it turns out that there is room for such operators and can be really successful.
After all, we don’t have to go too far for examples.
In February this year, we informed you about the launch of the virtual operator Mobilking in Poland.
In just half a year, this operator managed to acquire more than 100 thousand customers and become the fifth largest operator there.
Behind Mobilking is the financial group Penta, which owns U:fona, among others, in the Czech Republic.
The advantage of virtual operators is the ability to focus on a much more specific target group.
In order to function effectively, they need far fewer customers than a classic operator.
They do not carry with them the relatively high cost of the construction, operation and maintenance of the mobile network.
In the world, virtual operators usually profile themselves as low-cost - they offer cheap calls and SMS, but this is often balanced by a narrower range of services.
For example, Tesco Mobile in the UK offers SMS at least half as cheap as its competitors.
However, as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, the bet on the novel target group can also be quite a good move.
This operator focuses specifically on men.
"The right guys choose Mobilking - an operator they like and can trust," says David Seibertz CEO of the Mobile Entertainment Company, operating this virtual operator.
It is hard to say whether a similar concept as in Poland could catch in our country.
Miroslav Čepický, spokesperson for Vodafone, said: “The Czech market is relatively small for the segment approach on which most virtual operators are based.
Moreover, it is relatively saturated in terms of service offerings."
No chance in the Czech Republic, mobile operators say
However, it seems almost certain that if there is a virtual mobile operator in the Czech Republic, it will not be Mobilking.
"We are talking about the expansion of this successful project, but in the Czech Republic the negotiations do not look very promising.
Rather, Mobilking will be launched in other countries of our region," Jana Studničková, spokesperson for the Penta financial group, told Mobil.cz in a telephone interview.
Indirectly, it confirmed that the existing mobile operators in the Czech Republic are definitely not inclined to this idea.
Rather, on the contrary, they try to do everything they can to prevent any potential competitor.
The GTS Novera Group has not hidden the interest in launching a virtual mobile operator for a long time, which would like to take another step towards becoming a real competitor to Telefónika O2 in the field of corporate customers.
“We are very interested in offering our customers not only fixed but also mobile telecommunications services.
And the sooner the better.
We have repeatedly discussed this possibility with all Czech mobile operators.
We have already managed to move forward with some of them in negotiations," says Pavel Kaidl, the group's press spokesman.
Maybe it's flashing for better times.
From unofficial information, it seems that the first virtual operator should be expected by the end of the year.
For now, however, its creation is accompanied by an impenetrable wall of silence.
"At the moment, we do not believe that there is room for the creation of a full-fledged virtual operator on the Czech market.
The Czech market is very specific compared to other markets.
So far, we have not been approached by any entity with a comprehensive and serious project in this area," Vlastimil Sršeň from the Telefónika O2 press department told Mobil.cz.
Other operators also refer to the specificity of the Czech market.
T-Mobile press spokesperson Martina Kemrová adds in a rare agreement with O2: "So far, we have not seen any viable and mutually beneficial business project on which to continue to build."
He adds: "A virtual operator will hardly appear in the T-Mobile network by the end of the year.
At this point, we would already have to have a specific agreement on the table in order to consider in this short term."
Vodafone is focusing its attention rather on fulfilling the requirements of its own 3G license.
Miroslav Čepický says: "We are open to meeting potential virtual operators, especially in the area of cost-sharing and infrastructure.
This is what we consider to be the most beneficial in terms of customers.
Vodafone’s main strategy in this area is to find a partner to build a shared network for fast mobile internet.”
Responsible authorities - with operators one hand
The progress of mobile operators can be easily understood, the entry of another operator would mean an increase in competition, would lead to a fall in prices and thus a decrease in their profits.
So why make it easier for such a competitor?
The fact that when operators care about something, they can pull together, is also evidenced by the tussle around the creation of U:fon.
Perhaps the greatest pressure towards CTU went at the time of the creation of U:fon from T-Mobile.
This is evidenced by publicly available information from the CTU website.
But now U:fon is a reason to be an argument why not to admit a virtual operator.
Martina Kemrová commented: "The competitive environment of the mobile market was recently further enhanced by the entry of a fourth mobile operator into the market.
With regard to the nature of the mobile market in the Czech Republic, it is clear that the entry of another player would place high demands on him and especially for his services."
However, due to this approach of mobile operators, it is directly striking the complete disinterest of Czech regulators.
It is not just the position of CTU, which unfortunately does not have the power to interfere in the Czech Republic - unlike the Great Britain and other developed countries - it does not have the power to interfere in competition.
These belong exclusively to the Office for the Protection of Competition (ÚOHS).
However, he took his typical attitude to the whole issue.
"The entry of a virtual operator into the mobile market would be possible after a contract between the mobile operator and the virtual operator for the lease of the necessary infrastructure was concluded.
No such contract has been concluded yet, because the offer of potential candidates was probably not sufficiently interesting for conventional operators," Kristián Chalupa from the Department of External Relations of the Office said in response to our question.
The statement thus formulated in this way will not surprise the representatives of the operators.
From the office, which is supposed to represent the interests of consumers and, among other things, to ensure that no one abuses their position in the market, is more than considered.
Especially when Kristián Chalupa adds: "At foreign countries, where virtual operators normally operate, we can observe that their entry into the market has contributed to lowering prices for mobile phone services."
However, the pressure for the correct functioning of the market environment and the fall in prices are not among the interests of the Office.
In fact, the only thing that is shocking about the whole case is the touching harmony of the three mobile operators, which results from their reactions.
The question of whether it is really just a coincidence is offered on its own.
Like the exact same price of gasoline at gas stations, it is certainly only the work of chance and a hard competition.
"The Office has not found signs of anti-competitive conduct on this matter and therefore has no reason to intervene in some way.
None of the operators has a dominant position, so they have adequate increased responsibility for their market dealings.
The necessary tools for opening the mobile market for virtual operators are probably lacking in the telecommunications regulator," Chalupa said in his statement.
Interpretation of the dominant position in the market is one of the many points of contention.
Of course, there is an analysis of relevant markets prepared by CTU, according to which telecommunications are the only market from the point of view of competition.
In such a market, of course, none of the Czech operators have a dominant position.
However, some legal experts offer a different view - the creation of a virtual operator is always required to be the consent of the network operator.
And the mobile operator - has quite logically - on its network monopoly.
So in a certain segment, it necessarily has to be dominant.
However, even if we do not concede this argument, it should be at least a warning to the Office that three mobile operators are doing the same thing.
At the same time, complaints from a number of interested parties (including the aforementioned company GTS Novera) show that they encounter very similar obstacles when dealing with all operators.
The strengthening of responsibility on CTU is then a relatively common trick in telecommunications, by which the Office keeps its hands off the matter.
We have already met him in several similar cases.
Unfortunately, until the recently adopted amendment to the Telecommunications Act, the extension of the powers of CTU to the area of competition in telecommunications could not be enforced, although many experts expected to improve the situation.
This must be known more than well, but apparently their interests are elsewhere.
It's possible when no one's looking
At the same time, the functioning of pseudo-virtual operators, of which there are several in Czech mobile networks, remain unnoticed.
These are companies issuing their own price lists of mobile telephone services, but only partially public.
These are usually multi-level marketing companies.
Its own mobile telephone services are offered by Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and many others.
The price lists of these companies usually get to the chosen ones.
The magic is that the company acts as a classic corporate customer to the operator, who orders a large number of SIM cards.
As a distinguished customer, he will then receive special price (and other) offers.
The problem is that the terms and conditions of all Czech mobile operators prohibit a similar resale.
"If there were cases you are talking about, it could be a violation of the terms and conditions that we would deal with and could result in the termination of cooperation with the company," Martina Kemrová said.
However, it is unlikely that such activities would be brought to the responsible people of mobile operators.
In particular, in the case of the three companies mentioned, it can be thousands of customers.
None of the operators opposes such a procedure.
They have significant profits from the activities of these companies and, unlike real virtual operators, do not threaten them in any way with their own official marketing.
Miroslav Čepický points out possible problems: "The law allows such speculation, but only a negligible percentage of customers use the services of these companies.
In addition, they have to accept that the SIM card in their phone is not in their name, so they cannot have it fully as ordinary customers of mobile operators."
This should be at least strange to CTU.
In addition, another question is being raised for the Office.
If mobile operators close their eyes to a similar procedure, why do they block the formation of a virtual operator?
It should be added that the Office has relatively strong powers to detect such activities, and if it does not want to, it may not be satisfied with the explanation of operators that they have no idea about such a thing and their terms and conditions prohibit it.
When we won't be the most expensive
As has already been made in the text several times, the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market brought a significant drop in prices for services.
In virtually all countries where virtual operators were created, classical operators tried to defend their creation more or less.
The arguments they used were practically identical - too small, possibly too saturated, problems with the quality of services, etc.
In developed countries, however, it was at these times that regulators intervened, defending not the interests of mobile operators, but by their customers.
Whether by formal measures or informal pressure, they then achieved that the first virtual operator was created and another one was packed on it.
Unfortunately, the Czech regulators are tossing the whole case like a hot potato.
From our experience, we cannot get rid of the impression that the ambiguity in the competencies in these cases is more than useful.
But let's not throw flint into the rye.
If behind-the-scenes information is correct and the virtual operator will show up in our country very soon, the Czech mobile market may be moving again.
If any of the operators admit the creation of a virtual mobile operator, it will hardly be able to remain indifferent to the refusal (discriminating) of other interested parties.
And maybe we'll stop calling more expensive than in the rest of Europe.
