Listen to four versions of the Czech national anthem.
On Sunday, Prime Minister Mirek Topolánek on the occasion of Czech Statehood Day ceremonially presented new recordings of the national anthem Where My Home.
The national theatre orchestra was newly recorded by the National Theatre Orchestra under the direction of Jiří Bělohlávek.
There are four versions - with male or female solo singing, in choral performance and instrumental version.
Kateřina Kněžínková and Adam Plachetka took over.
The authors of the anthem’s modifications are Otakar Jeremiah and Jaroslav Krček.
On the server iHNed.cz you can listen to all four versions.
Bělohlávek considers the Czech national song to be one of the most beautiful hymens.
He has previously told Czech Radio that he deliberately selected singers with young representative voices for singing solo variants, which are distinctive and popular.
"I have been trying to make sure that the choirs from the beginning and then I also tried to make sure that they have a clear diction, so that the text would be well understood, to resonate," he said.
The Czech national anthem will celebrate its 175th anniversary next year.
The song Where My Home was first heard in 1834 on the boards of the Estates Theatre in the original Czech play Fidláček Josef Kajetán Tyl, accompanied by music by František Škroup.
It gained popularity and people spontaneously took her as their own.
The first stanchion of the song then after the establishment of Czechoslovakia in 1918 became a natural part of the national anthem.
