Prague Public Transport will also take a chip for the first time on Wednesday
Wednesday 1. October 2008 will go down in the history of the Prague Public Transport Company as the date when the first passengers will enter the metro, trams and buses, who will have an electronic coupon in their pocket instead of a paper ticket.
At this point, it can get about a hundred thousand people who own the Opencard chip card.
Passengers can buy a 30-day and 90-day and annual coupon (which will be valid from 1 January 2009) and at the same time have their chip card recorded in the information centers and workplaces of the Transport Company in the metro stations Muzeum, Můstek, Nádraží Holešovice, Anděl, Roztyly, Letňany, Kobylisy, Rajská zahrada, Kačerov and Luka.
Coupons can also be bought online from yesterday on the website of the Transport Company www.dpp.cz.
More than four hundred customers used the service until the afternoon.
Those who start using the online store can definitely forget about the dispensing windows in metro stations, where they have so far had to regularly stand on long queues for paper tickets.
They buy the coupon over the Internet and upload it to them on the Opencard in one of the thirteen branches of the Municipal Library.
"At these places, a trained service counter is available to passengers, which will help those interested with an online purchase and also upload a purchased coupon to their card," said project spokesman Martin Opatrný.
In addition to libraries, it will be possible to upload electronic coupons on Opencard also in self-service automata, which are mounted in several metro vestibules.
What do these machines look like?
They are red, they resemble ticket markers and passengers may have already noticed them in the metro stations Roztyly, Budějovická, I. P. Pavlova, Florenc and Vltavská.
"Now there are five of them in the city, but by the end of the year there should be eighty," Opatrný added.
