Turkish diplomatic horizons expand
Long before Turkey began to try to join the European Union, European powers longed to penetrate deep into the Turkish border.
On the eastern shore of the Bosphorus, perhaps only twenty steps in Asia, stands one of the best monuments of this failed imperial ambition.
The Hydarpasha railway station was designed by two German architects Otto Ritter and Helmut Cona in the neo-Renaissance style.
Tourist guides will tell you.
The building sits astride at the end of the platforms with a tower on every corner of the front, indistinguishable from some provincial German town hall.
The stone is dirty.
The whole building is slowly falling apart.
But once you get inside the vaulted cash register, you can no longer have doubts about the size of the business whose westernmost gate was the station.
The station was opened by the German consortium of Anatoly-Gladi Corporation in August 1908.
Germany, which was late in the game of empires, intended to realize its ambitions to dominate the Middle East with the help of this railway, which was supposed to lead to Damascus, Baghdad and further into the territory that is now Saudi Arabia.
But Germany's imperial ambitions collapsed during the First World War.
Their tracks were invaded by Lawrence of Arabia and his irregular forces.
Relative isolation from the surrounding areas, created by the frozen borders of the Cold War, is gone
British and colonial forces advanced from Egypt and pushed the Turks and their German allies out of Palestine and Syria.
And there was also bad news for Hydarpasha.
In 1917, an ammunition train explosion destroyed its elaborate roof.
Turkish sources say it was sabotage.
Since then, it has gradually crumbling and history bypasses it.
But today this gateway to Anatolia and beyond serves - at least symbolically - to enhance the expanding horizons of Turkish diplomacy.
The ruling Justice and Development Party - AKP - has created a completely new foreign policy for the country.
The relative isolation from the surrounding areas, created by the frozen borders of the Cold War, is gone.
Now a new policy is being applied - Turkey is engaged.
It is noteworthy that the Turkish government has good relations with Israel and Syria, with the Palestinian factions of Hamas and Fatah, with Iraq and Iran, and of course with the European Union and the United States.
In order to review the parameters of this new policy, I boarded a night train to the Turkish capital Ankara, where I was supposed to meet one of the leading AKP experts on foreign policy, Turkish MP Suat Kinniklioglu.
The next morning - about ten and a half hours later - after a courging drive on the tracks, which was recalled by the old-world rhythms of the well-known documentary Night Mail, I arrived in the Turkish capital, designed as a new city for a secular state that wants to turn its back on its Ottoman past.
However, the AKP, with its well-known Islamist roots, represents a shift in the paradigms of the Turkish consensus.
In the west, she aroused suspicions, especially in Washington.
The taxi brought me to the main tent of the AKP, an ultra-modern stone and metal building, deliberately built in an unfolding suburb, surrounded by half-built department stores and power-to-power dealerships, where middle managers in business suits - both men and women - meet to make early morning shops.
Suat Kinniklioglu could easily be a centre-right politician from almost every other European political party.
Jacket, tie, I'm sure he had Blackberry, too.
"The party's foreign policy goal is to reintegrate Turkey into its immediate vicinity.
The Cold War was an anomaly," he told me.
Turkey has been cut off from its restraint.
Today he has to look east and west at the same time.
It was no choice.
It must have done both.
"But I'm sure there will be a moment," I asked, "when will Turkey possibly have to decide?"
"Turkey," he said, "doesn't wish for such a decision to have to take place."
Then he stressed what almost everyone with whom I spoke here said almost by heart: Turkish relations not only with the Middle East, but also with the Caucasus and the surroundings of the Black Sea are as much for the benefit of Europe and the United States as Turkey.
With Turkey on board, Europe as a whole can, metaphorically speaking, take these tracks east to Asia and the Middle East.
Back to Hydarpasha station, after another mostly sleepless night, I was thinking about the two German lords Herr Ritter and Herr Cona watching this building stand up a century ago.
How surprised they would be if they found that European ambitions in the Middle East could now be, largely, in Turkish hands.
And when I was waiting in the harbor for the ferry back through the Bosphorus, I remembered that in those days Turkey was called the "sick man of Europe".
So it seems that at least at the time there was not much doubt which continent would be entitled to this fascinating country.
