Honda attacks its bestseller for the second time
In the month of November, Honda will start selling the second generation of the Jazz.
If the predecessor of this single-space vehicle already had considerable space, it now offers an even more spacious interior.
This includes improved engines that increase driving comfort and allow greater fuel savings.
Evolution rather than revolution.
This is the second generation of the Honda Jazz.
Although from an aesthetic point of view, the lines of the new Jazz are very similar to the previous model, there have been many changes in this single-space car.
It is necessary to mention, for example, innovative design, a new platform, larger dimensions and new engines.
Before we explore the new model, it should be noted that the new Jazz is coming to market six years after the launch of the first generation.
Therefore, the first thing we notice is the fact that Honda needed a shorter period to rejuvenate this model than other manufacturers.
Although Jazz is a lesser-known model in Europe, it has become a phenomenon in other markets.
This is the case with Japan, the country where Jazz was the best-selling car in 2002, and also during this year's 2008.
It is in Japan that almost a million units have been sold since the launch of the Honda Jazz.
The second market was the old continent with about half a million sold pieces in six years.
Honda, however, aims to boost the new Jazz's sales in its category.
Thus, while in 2007 this Japanese company sold a total of 83 000 Honda Jazz, in 2009 the estimates are 100 000 cars, which would mean an increase of 17% on the European market.
In terms of the Spanish market, Honda has sold a total of 5,000 Jazz models since 2002, which translates to 6.7% of Honda's total sales in Spain.
As for the new generation of Jazz, the management of the Spanish branch expects to sell 2 000 pieces for the whole year.
It is the arrival of the new Jazz that will allow Honda to significantly ease the decline in sales in Spain.
The management of the carmaker thus expects to finish the year with a total of 22 000 units sold, which means 4,000 fewer than in 2007 and a decrease of 16%.
Despite this increase in sales, Honda increased its share of the Spanish market to 1.8%, compared to 1.6% from last year.
In 2010, the Japanese company expects it to reach 2%.
In order to achieve this share, Honda relies on the success of its next new model.
It is the Honda Insight, a five-door compact-sized hybrid with a length of 4.37 meters, from which the Japanese company expects to sell around 200 000 units per year worldwide.
In terms of markets, according to estimates by the Japanese manufacturer, 50% of Insight will sell in the United States, while the remaining percentages will be divided by the old continent and Japan.
The launch of the Honda Insight is expected in the first months of next year as soon as it is presented to the public in Valencia in January.
Compared to the first generation, all dimensions have increased in the new Jazz.
Its length increased up to 3.9 meters (five centimeters more), the width to 1.69 meters (two centimeters more) and the wheelbase of the axles to 2.5 meters, which means an extension of five centimeters.
On the contrary, the height did not change and is still 1.52 meters.
By increasing the dimensions, the interior space was also increased.
This advantage was achieved both by using a new platform and by storing the fuel tank in the middle of the car, which was already used in the previous Honda Jazz.
Also, the volume of the luggage compartment - which has a double bottom system - increased up to 399 liters, 19 litres more than the volume of luggage compartment at the first generation.
It should be noted that these dimensions occur in the 1.4 engine version, as the luggage compartment volume at the Honda Jazz 1.2 is 379 liters.
Another improvement in addition to external elements - such as the rear LED lights or the possibility of equipping the glazed panoramic roof - is easier access to the rear seats.
The door leading to the second row of seats allows the 80-degree opening angle compared to 67 in the first Jazz.
For the second generation of the Honda Jazz, the engines are also new.
Initially, this small model will be offered with two 1.2 and 1.4-liter gasoline engines.
Both engines use i-VTEC technology, which enables lower consumption, lower carbon dioxide emissions and deliver excellent improvements to the drive system at the same time with high torque in full engine speed.
The first 1.2-liter engine has a power of 90 hp at 6,000 rpm with a maximum torque of 114 Nm at 4,900 rpm.
This engine - which had 78 hp for the previous generation of the Jazz - has a consumption of 5.3 liters and emissions of 125 grams of CO2.
Compared to the previous engine, which has reached 83 hp for the previous generation, the current one will reach 100.
The Honda Jazz 1.4 with 100 hp combined consumption and a combined power of 5.2 grams of CO2.
