"Car bee" prevents collisions
This time, Nissan was inspired to advance in the development of anti-inclusive technologies in nature, specifically bees.
This Japanese company has created a robot that takes as a pattern of bee flying, preventing collisions.
This is Bio-mimetic Car Robot Drive, or BR23C, which represents the first step in precipitation prevention technologies.
Engineers of the Center for Technical Advances by Nissan Motor Co. robot, in collaboration with the Centre for Advances in Scientific and Technological Research, Japan, developed the prestigious Tokyo University of Japan.
According to Kazuhir Doie, CEO of public relations for technology, brand research and development, the BR23C is presented as an extension of Nissan's four zones of the Nissan security shield.
The robot is designed to strengthen the ability to prevent precipitation in the car of this brand.
During the flight, each bee creates its own personal space of oval shape, which closely resembles the Nissan safety shield.
The most important, however, are folded bees, which are able to see in all directions at an angle of more than 300 degrees, allowing the bee to fly in its personal space without stopping.
Engineers, when creating this visual function, designed what they called the laser localizer (Laser Range Finder).
It records obstacles that are located up to two meters in a radius of 180 degrees in front of the BR23C, calculates the distance of the object and sends a signal to the on-board microprocessor, which immediately converts it to a collision warning.
"The moment an obstacle is recorded, the robot imitates the bee movements and immediately changes the direction by turning the wheels to the right or even greater angle to prevent a collision.
The biggest difference from any existing system is the fact that all evasive maneuvers are completely instinctive.
If this were not the case, the robot would not be able to react quickly enough to avoid obstacles," explains Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Mobile Laboratory and chief engineer of the project.
Unlike bees, the robot cannot move upwards and downwards, its movement is limited to only two dimensions and the direction in which it is allowed by rotating its wheels, but not in an infinite number of directions and possibilities as with bees.
Therefore, in addition to acceleration and slowing, Nissan also used the rotation function to prevent the robots from colliding.
"The device only needs to process the information every few seconds and act according to these data.
It does not require the preservation of information or logical intuition from previous maneuvers, thanks to which it can function without interruption with just two dozen kB of memory.
It may surprise you, but we don’t talk about gigs or mega in our memory.”
This is the first step in the development of new technologies for the immediate prevention of precipitation, a technology that Nissan predicts use in series cars in a decade.
The robot uses lithium polymer batteries that are lighter and last longer than lithium-ion.
Another possible future use of this technology could be the incorporation of the unit into the GPS satellite navigation system, which would lead the driver to the destination and avoid obstacles on the road.
Drivers repeatedly caught with alcohol in their blood will have to install "alcolock"
The Ministry of the Interior requires that the driver with three administrative sanctions for driving under the influence of alcohol must install a system in his car that prevents him from starting the car drunk or if he does not breathe.
The proposal became known in June this year and is now included in the annual report of the Supreme Public Prosecutor’s Office, according to which it is a pilot project that will last one year.
Its aim is to return the driver to the wheel, so drivers will also have to undergo a course of traffic education.
In addition to the National Transport Safety Authority, the Directorate of Transport (DGT) and the Foundation of the Technology Institute for the Safety of Automobile Safety (FITSA) will also participate in this experience.
According to statistics, between 30 and 75% of motorists charged more than once for drunk driving, they will get behind the wheel again in this state.
Alcolock should prevent this as it is a system connected to a vehicle that measures the level of alcohol in the exhaled air and prevents the start-of-car if the driver does not breathe before or if a higher-than-permitted concentration of alcohol is recorded.
Its price exceeds 1 000 euros and the culprit himself would have to pay for it.
A study conducted in the US in 2007 showed that vehicles equipped with this device decreased by 65% during the first year since the introduction.
In Spain, it is expected that 115 people could save their lives every year.
The measure is limited to administrative sanctions for two reasons: to address this behaviour before it results in the offence.
And in order to help its implementation, because the legislation can be carried out in the usual way, but the necessary regulation of criminal provisions requires a change in the law.
The device is not yet available on the Spanish market in any sales version, although it has already been reinvented in some industrial vehicles and public service vehicles.
Tomorrow, the Congress of Deputies will vote on the PSOE proposal (Spain Workers' Socialist Party), in which it is recommended to install this system on school buses, as is the case in France.
