Interview - Blood that's sure
Heme-Québec celebrated the tenth anniversary of the founding and its president, dr. Francine Décary, she was rightly rejoicing because Hema-Québec became one of the most reliable and effective blood suppliers in the world.
Above all, he regained the public's trust, which was seriously shaken after the contaminated blood scandal in the 80's and 90's.
As is widely known, the state reserve of blood managed by the Transfusion Department of the Canadian Red Cross has been contaminated with the immune deficiency virus (HIV) virus and hepatitis C virus during the 80's.
Given this drama and the wave of public resentment, the Canadian government launched a public investigation in February 1994, chaired by Judge Horace Krever, which aimed to explain the circumstances that led to such a tragedy and to formulate a recommendation that such a disaster should not be repeated.
While Judge Krever delayed the report, some provinces set the run-to-equipment of a committee aimed at planning a new blood administration system in Canada.
In Quebec, the Gélinea Committee held this role.
After the Gélineau and Krever reports, two suppliers were set up in Canada: Hema-Québec, which was supposed to be managed by Quebec, and the Canadian blood company for supplying all provinces and both territories.
"When hem-Québec started its activities in 1998, barely 38% of people still had confidence in the Quebec blood system," recalls dr. Décary.
“The situation was daunting.
By a stapling effort to increase the safety of blood products and the constant work in this area over the coming years, we have regained the public’s trust,” he says, adding proudly that at the beginning of 2008, Héma-Québek’s nearly 94% of the Quebec population trusted Héma-Québek.
Dr. Décary, however, does not lose sight that "confidence is something very fragile".
Since its foundation on 28 September 1998, Hema-Québec has applied the principle of prudence.
“At that time, we witnessed many cases of human form of mad cow disease in Europe, a new variant of the disease called Creutzfeldt-Yoib’s disease,” says the woman, who has been leading the company since its foundation in 1998.
"And we had no idea if this disease could spread through blood.
We have therefore relied on one of the basic recommendations of the Krever and Gélineau's report, according to which when we do not know this and when the spread of a serious illness is at stake, in this case Creutzfeldt-Jakob's disease, which is characterized by brain degeneration inevitably leading to death, it is necessary to take an exclusionary measure.
In April 1999, we refused blood from people who had stayed in the UK since 1980 for more than a month.
A few years ago, it was safely proven that this disease was transmitted through the blood.
So this episode showed us that sticking to the principle of prudence was meaningful.”
In 1999, a much more accurate HIV-tested technique appeared on the market: nucleic acid (NAT) tests that make it possible to detect the presence of the virus itself in the donor blood directly, and not the presence of antibodies on which the tests used before.
NAT tests have made it possible to shorten the deaf period, which occurs between the moment of infection of the patient and the moment when the first viruses can be detected by our blood techniques, explains the specialist.
We have been able to short-term this period to less than a week.
We have made a substantial reduction in the risk that some donors might be infected without knowing it and without being able to figure it out.
These improvements have made it possible to significantly reduce the risk of getting AIDS through a blood transfusion.
The risk of receiving HIV-contaminated blood is now exposed to one in 12 million.
“By other words, it means that before someone becomes infected with HIV, 12 million blood products will need to be distributed.
Since Héma-Québec distributes 400 000 to 500 000 blood products every year, it will be 24 years before the first case of HIV transmission occurs through a blood product.
I believe that today we can get or prescribe the blood transfusion necessary to heal," says the head of the management of Héma-Québek.
“The challenge for the next decade is to preserve the safety of our products.
We never know what a diseased element can appear in the system.
Just last year, the chikungunya virus appeared on the island of Réunion, which, like the West Nile virus, is transmitted to the blood by stinging insects.
We need to be careful all the time," dr. continues. Décary and stresses that in addition to the safe supply, Héma-Québec must also take into account sufficient supply.
“Supplies are growing because the population is aging.
As a result of more aggressive cancer treatment, patients often need a new dose of red blood cells or platelets.
Population ageing also has consequences for a network of blood donors, which on average consists of only 3% Québeccas permissible for donation."
Any healthy person at least 18 years old, corresponding to the criteria of admissibility, but can donate blood only once every 56 days, that is, six times a year.
On average, 14% of people offering blood are not accepted because they are carriers of AIDS or malaria, for example, and whether they have visited a country where mud chills are ruled out for a year.
“With these 3%, we can maintain a condition that meets the needs of hospitals.
Deficiencies are very rare.
However, members of the network of donors need to be replenished in proportion to how they age and can no longer donate blood.
But persecuting people to give blood is difficult, especially to keep them and instigated them to become regular donors.
Life is so unbridled today that we rarely find an hour to donate blood,” says Francine Décary.
With an annual budget of $297 million, Hema-Québec supplies not only blood products, but also human tissue, as bone transplants, heart valves, eyeballs and skin, which is almost exclusively used for large burns.
These tissues are analyzed, processed and freeze before they are stored in Heme-Québek, which also manages a single public bank of blood from the umbilical cord in Quebec.
The umbilical cord, which was previously considered biomedical waste, abounds with cetal-rich blood, which can serve to treat serious diseases, such as leukemia.
"A few weeks ago, we celebrated the deposit of our thousands of blood samples from the umbilical cord to the bank and we assume that we will take over a thousand of them a year.
At the beginning of next year, we should start offering them for transplants," explains dr. Décary, who describes the cord blood collection program as very popular.
"Some moms are disappointed that they don't have access to it," because Hema-Québec does not have enough resources to offer this comprehensive and expensive program to all hospitals in Quebec.
