Opinions - Orwellian discos from Barrick Gold
In a September 17 edition, Le Devoir published a letter from Patrick J. Garvera, executive vice president of the Canadian mining company Barrick Gold.
With Orwellian logic, he confirms that the world's largest gold producer has launched a prosecution of three authors and a poor small publishing house for libel in order to spark "transparent public debate" and demand six million from them.
If it is true that judges are independent and impartial, they do not judge truthfulness, especially in the case of prosecution for libation, but the law.
Unsurprisingly, Garver is completely decaying this crucial distinction.
Or is Barrick Gold the best way to have a public debate to break anyone who dares to defend the opposite position?
Whatever the outcome of the process, the authors and publisher of Noir Canada (Black Canada) will be forced to spend respectable sums to be ready to defend themselves and fight in a very unbalanced battle with an army of attorneys supported by almost bottomless pockets of mining company.
After all, the tactics in these unbalanced struggles often lie in the ruins of the defendants in order to enforce conciliation proceedings, which will clog the mouth of the opposing party and, moreover, scare anyone who dares to devote himself to this matter.
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public debate, it should have presented its view of the whole thing to public opinion.
Contrary to what is happening in several countries where Barrick Gold operates, Canada is a debate under normal circumstances in the exchange of ideas, and not in battalion blows.
Therefore, mine companies were only enough to open up their books, their documentation and to establish a real debate through newspapers, media, publications and the financing of independent scientific teams that could bring light to the whole thing.
But Barrick Gold doesn’t seem to have confidence in public opinion, and smach musing petitions and letters in support of the authors of Noir Canada.
Perhaps Garver could explain how he can demand a "public debate" and at the same time despise the views of the same public?
It seems that this word in the vice president's world refers only to boldly paid lawyers, and not all Canadians; this is a rather narrow-minded conception of this concept.
In a democracy, even the nadipers have the right to speak.
Barrick Gold doesn't understand - or doesn't want to understand - that the public that supports authors and publishers Noir Canada does so primarily because it rejects brutal ways of mining society.
The public is ready to hear Barrick and judge the matter, but on the basis of a civilized exchange of arguments, not within what many perceive as a prosecution in which the defendant's mouth is to be blocked (as in its prosecution of the "public debate" by the way, Barrick has just given official calls to the authors of Noir Canada to officially notify them that they should stop using this term...).
Aside from Garver’s surreal speech, the prosecution of the initiated Barrick Gold is a direct attack on university freedom of inquiry and the search for truth that is essential for every democratic society.
Overall, it denies the right to cite credible sources and to the debate on facts and interpretations that represent the very basis of intellectual activity.
If in a country like Canada, it is impossible to study and discuss topics that do not like the rich companies of this world without exposing ourselves to repeated prosecutions, who else will be able to do it?
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public and transparent debate, it could have created it if it had followed the scientific standards used by Noir Canada.
He has the right to an answer.
The university environment to which we belong can manage debates and disagreements and resolve conflicts.
Barrick Gold's exaggerated lawsuit shows that despite what it claims, it doesn't have the slightest appetite to have a transparent debate.
For the university world, this is a loss, as well as for public debate in Canada, and it is time for governments to put in place measures to limit such a type of unjustified prosecution.
Wall Street Rescue Operations - Democrats and Republicans Understand Each other
The Bush administration and congressional leaders, both Republicans and Democrats, ended yesterday to reach an agreement on the biggest bait economic plan since the 1930s' Great Crisis.
A new version of the plan to use $700 billion to slow down the financial crisis that has been rocking Wall Street for months has yet to be approved by both houses of Congress.
In particular, it assumes: better control of elected representatives over its application, new mechanisms to pay the deposits of public money, new measures to capture the number of houses confiscated due to non-payment, as well as the right to monitor the amount of wages paid to the executives of bailed companies.
U.S. Treasury Secretary Henry Paulson, Speaker of the House of Representatives Nancy Pelosi and Republican representative at the negotiating table, Senator Judd Gregg, announced the good news yesterday a few minutes after midnight, after the end of a two-day negotiating marathon.
“We have made great progress and have come to an agreement that will be effective in the markets,” said Henry Paulson, a statement from the Bush administration.
"Everything was done to make the real economy and ordinary Americans safe from the crisis on Wall Street," the Democrat explained.
“This is a crucial point: if we don’t, the trauma, the chaos and disruption of the daily lives of Americans will be enormous,” said Republicd Judd Gregg.
Over the last few hours, negotiations have started at the maximum speed for fear of the effect of another failure on the mood of investors.
The set time limit was the opening of markets this morning.
The two candidates for the US president were invited to the negotiations later, and both expressed their opinion more on the agreement, but did not forget to express their dissatisfaction with the need to resort to such an extreme solution.
Democratic Senator Barack Obama has added an agreement on some measures, especially the one to allow owners to maintain their residence and measures on the wages of senior state-salvities seniors.
“When we ask taxpayers to take special measures because of the irresponsibility of some people, there is nothing more to congratulate themselves.
However, these measures are necessary," he explained on the waves of television.
His Republican opponent, John McCain, who was asked by another station, whether he will vote for the proposed plan, replied: "I'd like to see the details, but I hope so."
"The gross traits I've read [supplier] are concerned that this is something we're all going to have to spend and with which to move forward.
Choring inaction is simply unacceptable," he said.
The goal of the 700-billion-dollar plan is to buy out questionable claims and risky and unsaleable assets of American financial institutions with taxpayers' money.
The plan comes after 14 months of crisis unleashed by the bursting of the housing bubble, which first led to the collapse of risky mortgage loans (subprimes), then passed to other, more widespread forms of credit (PCAA) and resulted in a cash freeze and in the dissolution of banks and financial institutions.
The fall in last week's first draft deal is due to Republican MPs.
Ever since Democrats have agreed to the fact that some of the "toxic" assets of companies with difficulties will only be guaranteed by the government, but will not buy them, there is a belief that the hopeless situation is over.
In an effort to approximat the contradictory views in Congress, a measure was attached to the fact that the government will be able to introduce new fees to help it recover its deposit if it will have to take losses for five years as a result of the program.
The new plan envisages a first-largest €250 billion deposit, to which it will be possible to add an additional $100 billion if the president sees it necessary.
A $350 billion deposit is expected to be approved by Congress in a new vote.
In exchange for its help, Washington will acquire stakes in rescued companies, which will pay dividends in the event of profit and which will be able to sell again when it is all over.
The federal government will be able to delay the seizure procedures of the real estate associated with the loans covered by the plan, as well as to set limits on the amount of remuneration and compensation paid to executives of the affected firms.
The masterminds of the plan would like to submit it to the vote in the House of Representatives already today and in the Senate on Wednesday.
Despite all the efforts made, it is not yet certain whether their plan will have the green light.
Yesterday, voices were further up against the project in both the Republican and Democratic camps.
"It is quite obvious that Washington can't hear you," Republican Scott Garrett, a member of the House Financial Commission, said in a statement.
“Yes, we have a serious financial problem.
Yes, there are solutions.
Earning on taxpayers is not a solution.”
Democratic representative Brad Sherman, the moderator of a group of congressmen nicknamed the "committees of skeptics," presents the whole thing differently, but comes to the same conclusion.
"Four hundred esteemed economics professors, among them three Nobel Prize winners, have written to us: we ask Congress not to rush too much and examine carefully which path to take," he said.
At the same time, it was reaffirmed in Europe that this crisis is a world crisis.
After the extraordinary meeting, three Benelux countries announced a partial nationalization of the Fortis banking group for 11.2 billion euros ($16.3 billion).
The intervention of the governments of Belgium, the Netherlands and Luxembourg became necessary after the French bank BNP Paribas announced that it was withdrawing from the purchase of its competitor, which has been on the verge of a meltover since it lost 2 billion euros (2.9 billion USD) as a result of the risky credit for the purchase of real estate in the United States.
Fortis employs 85 000 people, one of Europe's top 20 banks and among the ten largest insurers.
"We will not lose this money," Dutch Finance Minister Wouter Bos said yesterday.
"In return, we earn the right to vote in the bank and influence.
And it is the savers and households who appreciate it in today’s uncertain times.”
On the other side of the English Channel, the British government seems to have begun nationalizing another bank affected by the financial crisis.
According to the English press, the government was supposed to take over all existing loans to Bradford and Bringley, of which more than $41 billion ($75.5 billion) were loans to buy real estate.
According to its announcement yesterday, the Spanish bank Santander will buy branches and accounts of British bank clients.
Bradford and Bringley will be the second bank after Northern Rock, which the UK government has had to nationalize since the start of the financial crisis.
Paul Newman (1925-2008) - Death of a socially engaged icon
His beauty with azure eyes long represented his trump card, according to others a weakness.
Did this American actor get out with a charming smile from daffynism?
Yes and no.
The slenderness, sensitivity, and the unceasing talent that possessed him also distanced him from the power category that begets real stars.
But what a long-distance runner he was!
Paul Newman died on Friday at the age of 83 at the age of 83 at the age of his banquet in Connecticut as a result of lung cancer and remains one of the last icons of the fat years of American cinema.
Less spectacular than Brando, who was similar to and long as his rival on the screen, Newman was a more cautious actor, certainly a more fragile, but also an apostle of freedom and the disintegration of dramatic conventions.
Mixed blood often breeds beautiful children.
Born in Ohio in 1925, his father was a German Jew and a Hungarian mother.
From these European roots, one of the famous faces of the American dream was born.
Without an exaggerated ego, which is the last sign of quality.
Because in it, all this country in love with a self-made man, a fighter at the Pacific War, wounded in a battle who studied acting in Yale in the early 1950s, then attended New York's Actor's Studio and celebrated a triumph at the theatre, on television and soon in the film.
The same man who fought for civil rights was also a racing driver who placed second at the 24-hour race at Le Mans in 1979, and a sexual symbol at the same time, despite the fact that since 1958 he has formed a model pair with actress Joanne Woodward.
With it, the downsides of this hidden, discreet, socially engaged star are also leaving, allergic to the fuss of their own show-business, which will forever remain mysterious to some extent.
A decent man, in the noblest sense of the word.
Paul Newman's departure this weekend caused the film lovers to be drunk, while his great roles rival each other on the black screen of memories.
After him, he has been defining for more than half a century of the ever-changing American seventh art.
The charming cowboy of Butch Cassidy and the Sundance Kid (1969), a young man who rejects his sensual wife (Elizabeth Taylor) in the Cat on a hot roof, Tennessee Williams' 1958 adaptation of Tennessee Williams.
From the less distant past (1990) we recall his sensitive Mr. Bridge, disturbed at an advanced age by marriage, who did not meet all expectations.
So many other Newman Pauls went down in history.
Boxer Rocky Graziano, abused, violent, memorable delinquent from Somebody Up There Likes Me, Robert Wis, a role designed for James Dean, taken after his death, which in 1956 put Newman into true acquaintance.
Sympathetic gangster in the absolutely great The Sting, Oscar for Best Picture in 1973.
The bitter and vengeful billiards player in the amazing The Hustler Robert Rossen (1961), played by Martin Scorsese, the same character in The Color of Money, which will bring him the only Oscar out of seven nominations in 1987.
This face wandering in ages, that was him.
And he again.
In his professional career, different epochs compete with each other.
The young people know him mainly thanks to the iconic Slap Shot George Roy Hill (1977) from the role of Reggie Dunlop, an unconventional hockey coach.
Fans reunited with him in 1994 at The Hudsucker Proxy of the Coen Brothers.
He then concluded his career as the godfather of the Irish mafia in the Road to Perdition Sam Mendes in 2003.
Unlike several film legends, which left the craft relatively soon, Newman remained in the business for a long time, even though he condemned Hollywood with its gliders, flamboyance and concessions.
French filmmaker Bertrand Tavernier regarded him, not without humor, "a lively challenge of underplaying", judging that he pushed too hard in his performances.
For the beautiful Paul Newman, to whom the roles came as a tray, the profession was not always so tender.
However, he played the first lovers less often than outsiders: neurotics, alcoholics, crooks, and losers, whose decay and rebellions reflected in his perfect traits.
As director Newman, he revealed the little-known aspects of his shy sensitivity.
His 1968 film Rachel, Rachel (based on the novel by Canadian Margaret Laurence), in which his wife Joanne Woodward, played a leading role, gives a sensitive female portrait full of melancholy.
He gave his son Scott, whom he lost for an overdose, in 1984, the Harry and Son film, a work full of shame and sadness.
In the inrrential honors Newcastle yesterday, his great friend and former comrade-in-combatant Robert Redford (playing together in The Sting and the Butch Cassidy and the Sundance Kid) grievously stated: "His presence made my life and this country better."
Magnificence, love of life, such are the main qualities of the deceased actor.
Apart from his legendary career, the great civil rights activist, ecology, independent film, the opponent of the decline of Hollywood is also leaving.
His portrait was used to seeing vinegar, sauces, biscuits and other foods on bottles of wine vinegar, but it may have been quite tasteless to us, although it was initially a gag.
However, the profits from the sale went to the account of his Foundation for a difficult childhood.
So, rather than be lulled by glory, Newman engaged in society until the last moment.
He left a letter to his five daughters containing these sentences: "Always and to the end, your father was grateful to his happy planet.
It was an honor that I could be here.”
And for us, it was an honor to be able to follow the career of such a bright and generous American artist.
And besides, after all, a model citizen.
What was produced in the Zuschlag & spol. invoice factory?
Before long, 8. October, the trial will begin in criminal proceedings against János Zuschlaga and his associates.
The politician and his associates, in addition to other crimes, including forgery of deeds, are accused of fraud committed by a long-term and systematically criminal organization, as a result of which extremely significant damages were caused.
According to the prosecutor, they used the money raised in public tenders for their own purposes and often documented the fulfillment of the tasks with fictitious invoices.
The money from the state and self-government - the total of approximately 65 million forints - went partly to the treasury of the Fiatal Baloldal organization, partly into the pockets of individuals.
The manner also reported by the investigating authority was that the money obtained in the tenders was collected on the basis of invoices for which there was no real consideration, and the commitments made by the associations never fulfilled.
According to the indictment, a large proportion of invoices were false.
The forms for these invoices came from the Józsefváros market, the round stamps were made in Kisunhalasi.
The names of which companies should make invoices were decided, among other things, on a tour along the northern bank of the Balaton, to which István Ladas János Zuschlag sent István Ladas.
According to his testimony, the former was supposed to look for guesthouses and restaurants.
In them, he asked for accounts for his consumption, according to whose model the invoices submitted in the framework of public tenders announced, inter alia, by the Ministry of Youth and Sport, the Ministry of Labour and Social Affairs, respectively the Self-Government of the Capital City, were then produced.
Invoices were mostly issued by István Lados with his partner András Őri, who, according to our information, most often wrote the reports needed to obtain subsidies.
On his "study journey" Lados looked for a pub.
According to two invoices issued by Zuschlage and his associates in 2003, this hospitality catering facility for the 90-member group from the Biztos Pont association.
However, so many people would not fit into this facility at once, according to the company’s manager.
Likewise, the invoice issued in the summer of 2002 by the formal and content errors was swarmed by the foundation called Jobb Jövőért, later Együtt and Harmadik Évezredért.
The guesthouse in Badacsonytomaya had only three rooms, more than ten people could not sleep in it one evening, yet one hundred and thirty guests were listed on the invoice.
However, fillers of forms with a rich imagination overdid it even when they introduced on the documents a company dedicated to the hospitality industry - Pigal s. r. o., in whose accounts, according to the information provided to the public prosecutor's office, documents sounding in the name Jobb Jövőért and Hoppá did not even figure.
The company manager Győző Farkas told hvg.hu that when he was summoned to the prosecutor's office and showed him invoices, he immediately knew that they were fake documents.
"The name of our business and our tax number were on the stamp in the wrong place."
As he added, besides the formalities, the fact that according to the invoice they accommodated a hundred people, because they have only eleven rooms that do not have such a large capacity.
In addition, food has also been mentioned on the invoice, and their restaurant has not been working for a long time.
The outrageous invoice makers were not convinced that the Budapest travel agency is organizing only foreign trips, and on an invoice with cash payments, which also did not coincide with the company’s invoicing practice, they said foolishly as a travel mediation service around Hungary.
Moreover, as it emerged during the course of the investigation, they also said VAT in the document, although the organisation of trips to countries outside the European Union has been exempted from VAT.
The VAT level did not agree, among other things, the VAT level on four documents issued by Jobb Jövőért by Hotel Révfülöp s. r. o. The activities of the company are not covered by the 25 percent, but 15 percent VAT, in addition, the hotel employees issued only printed invoices, but the invoice produced was written by hand.
In addition, the "publishers" spoiled the invoice by saying, for example, at one company, how it came out thanks to the investigation of the Public Prosecutor's Office, as the activity carried out by the road transport of goods, which the company based originally on investment advice did not perform.
The fact that invoices are issued by the Együtt and Harmadik Évezredért Foundation and the XXI associations. The safety of the Kulturáris Egyesület and Biztos Pont fake, was also revealed because of formal deviations - the non-corresponding format of the invoice and the wrong stamp.
As in the case of Ravenna k. s. or the Sports Camp in Kunfehértó, whose representatives have denied issuing invoices.
For example, counterfeiters did not even notice that HIB s. r. o. from Nyíregyházy was at the time (2001), when a group from the Fiatal Városért association was eating, in liquidation, which is why, according to our information, the liquidation commissioner of the company also denied that he had issued the paper.
Invoices were kept consciously
The second group of invoients are those who knew to issue a fictitious invoice.
The Esély Budapestért Foundation issued accounts for about four million forints for the Harmadik Évezredért Foundation at the request of Fiatal Baloldal - Ifyú Szocialisták.
According to the indictment, the head of Collab s. r. o. was prompted by one of the accused Ludovic Györfi to issue a fictitious account.
Biogate s. r. o, currently in liquidation, which in 2003 supplied the Jobb Jövőért Foundation and Atlasz and Vörösfenyőyőyőyőr to the associations Atlas and Vörösfenyő invoices worth about five million forints, for which there was no actual economic activity.
Not even the movement of money, because the invoices created were later canceled, which, however, the organizations forgot to mention in their documents.
Another group of billing companies includes those that had ties to the defendants.
Thus, for example, Ivan Kubatov was an authorized representative of the Ukrainian executive of Delta Trió s. r. o., engaged in the trading of fuel and motor vehicles, based in Budapest, on which the company is not available.
The company issued several invoices for the sale of computer equipment worth approximately 18 million forints in October, November and December 2005.
According to the data obtained by the investigation, the Kishunhalaská company Cash Investment s. r. o., which was in liquidation since 14 September 2005, bought these invoices.
