Psychology trumping: why do we spend more money?
At auctions, customers are willing to spend more money, overestimate goods.
The neurological and economic foundations of this well-known - and seemingly irrational - behavior have been revealed to researchers from the field of neurology and economics at the University of New York.
According to their study, published in the journal Science, people do not want to lag behind in an eBay auction competition, so they prefer to pay too high a price.
The research, using an experimental auction, attempted to map the scheme of this "game" in the nervous system.
One group of volunteers planted, the other group participated in a live-action auction, while the active areas of the brain of experimental subjects were investigated using the functional magnetic resonance (fMRI method).
In both games, participants could win money, but during the game for the auction, an important element of which is to trump the other side, the whole unit found under the cerebral cortex, called the striatum, began to work intensively during the loss.
In addition to many other functions, this brain area plays a role in the "self-remutation" mechanism of the nervous system.
According to the researchers, it is therefore possible to explain the unscrupulous price by trying to avoid a sharp reaction of striata.
To support their theory, members of the research team from the ranks of economists carried out a financial cross-cutting survey.
Under different conditions, three groups appealed against one partner.
The control group was simply communicated what the real value of the product was, and they made the bets.
In addition, members of the next group were promised that if they came out of the game victorious, they will get $15 as a reward.
The third group, on the other hand, received $15 before the auction, but in the event of a loss, its members lost this money.
The difference between the two groups, therefore, all in all that was emphasized by one win and the other a loss.
However, members of the group playing "against the loss" were willing to go higher than the case in the control and "wine" group, which confirms the hypothesis of neurologists.
"These results cannot be deduced from any existing economic theory.
Until now, they have explained phenomena observable during auctions with the joy of victory and avoidance of risk.
Only neurological imaging methods helped us solve the contradiction between these two theories so that we have now come to a third explanation,” said Andrew Schotter, a professor at the University of New York’s Faculty of Economics.
Hepatitis: when to consult a doctor?
Approximately half a billion people worldwide suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C infection, and in Hungary this chronic liver disease is listed among the leading causes of death.
The number of domestic cases of hepatitis infection is estimated at one hundred thousand, but only seven thousand of them are treated. The reason for this is that the sick often do not know that they are infected.
The name hepatitis is a collective name of infectious liver damage caused by various viruses.
There are many similarities in their symptoms, the symptomatic is inflammation of the liver and jaundice, but the causative agents of the disease and their caused diseases differ from each other.
The hepatitis viruses, depending on the causative diseases, are spread in two main ways: hepatitis A and E by the digestive system (for example, infected foods, water), hepatitis B, C, D and other viruses with blood and body fluids (sperm, vaginal secretion, saliva).
In any case, travellers should protect themselves with vaccination against virus A and B, there is no vaccine against the type C virus.
Symptoms of hepatitis A appear two to three weeks after ingestion of infected food, usually accompanied by nausea, weakness, abdominal problems, the urge to vomit.
Then jaundice forms on the skin and eye whites, lighter stools and darken the urine. Treatment can take two to three weeks.
Every year, a million people worldwide die from a more serious kind of disease, liver cancer and liver cirrhosis caused by hepatitis B.
The main reason is that, according to estimates, only one in ten infected person is medically treated.
Also, hepatitis C can have very serious consequences: if not treated, it can lead to liver cirrhosis or liver cancer.
Most of those infected do not even know about their disease, the causative agent of the disease destroys the liver cells insidiously, and so the first symptoms occur in many cases in 20-30 years.
Therefore, early prevention is very important, the implementation of regular descripture.
In three groups, this disease occurs much more often than on average: among people who had a blood transfusion before 1991, among drug users and among people with tattoos.
Currently, the expected global number of individuals infected with chronic hepatitis C virus is 200 million.
Since the disease can prove already routine laboratory examination, a person should contact his/her general practitioner if he notices any symptom of unknown origin.
With early detection, the disease is treatable, the virus can be removed from the body, preventing contagiousness and preventing the development of cancer.
September 30 is a world day of hepatitis, which was organized by organizations representing the sick for the first time worldwide in 2004.
Its aim is to draw attention to chronic inflammation of the liver caused by these viruses, the causes of its origin and the importance of early recognition of the disease.
