What would be the best method of developing technologies capable of preventing collisions, if not imitation of obstacle detectors occurring in the world of nature?
For example, in bees.
The initial strategic idea of a surprising project, presented at the Japanese CEATEC trade fair, was inspired by Nissan bumblebees engineers. It was about building a new generation of collision-refighting systems.
In collaboration with the University of Tokyo, Nissan has engineered a biomimetic robotic robotic control system, a robotic minicar that is equipped with the properties of bees, with the ultimate goal of helping to create a system that can eliminate all collisions.
"During the flight, each bee creates its own personal space of oval shape, which actually closely resembles our safety protective cover," Kazuhiro Doi, CEO of the brand's brand for technology PR and research and development, explained at the Kazuhiro Doi exhibition.
An important role is played by folded eyes, allowing bees to see in all directions in a viewing angle of more than 300 degrees.
To copy the function of the folded eye, the engineers reached for the idea of a laser rangefinder.
It identifies obstacles at a distance of up to 2 meters in the BR23C field of view, calculates their distance and sends a signal to the on-board microprocessor, which is immediately transformed into an operation aimed at preventing collisions.
The obstacle is captured within a fraction of a second, then the robotized car starts to imitate the movements of the bee and turns the wheels in the range needed to prevent the collision immediately changes direction.
Unlike any existing system, this switching manoeuvre takes place in a completely instinctive way.
“If this were not the case, a robotic car would not have been able to react quickly enough to avoid obstacles,” explains Toshijuki Ando, Head of the Mobility Laboratory and the Robotic Car Project.
It must react instinctively and immediately, as this technology suits the most vulnerable and internal layer of the safety protective packaging, inside which the collision is currently considered inevitable.
The whole process must reflect what the bee does to avoid other bees.
This process must not take longer than the blink of an eye.
However, unlike bees, this movement cannot be directed upwards, downwards or diagonally, it can only be two-dimensional and only in the direction in which the wheels can be rotated.
Instead of the endless possibilities offered by bees when avoiding, only the possibility of revolving movement, acceleration and deceleration was applied in the case of a robotic car.
The BR23C uses lithium-polymer batteries that are lighter and have a higher energy density, which means they have a longer lifespan than lithium-ion variants.
According to Ando, the important instinctive, intelligent reaction, is not the ability to process, much less data storage.
This mechanism must process and respond to only a few incoming signals per second.
There is no need for him to store them and respond using intuitive logic based on data from previous manoeuvres, so it is constantly using only a memory the size of a few kilobytes.
It does not need memory with giga- or megabyte capacity.
This is the first step towards developing a technology used to avoid immediately, which Nissan estimates could get into mass-produced cars within ten years.
Another possibility of application may be the connection of the unit with the GPS satellite navigation system, which, after avoiding the path of the lying obstacles, would lead the motorist to the specified final destination.
